a pretty nice situation to be in.

23
00:01:00,781 --> 00:01:03,942
So I'm just going to talk about four kind of common

24
00:01:04,022 --> 00:01:06,703
themes that have been in the development of the industry

25
00:01:06,743 --> 00:01:07,003
this year.

26
00:01:09,310 --> 00:01:14,154
But first of all, because I'm sure there'll be a range of levels of expertise and knowledge

27
00:01:14,234 --> 00:01:19,139
about accessibility, I'm just going to assume nothing and start from the start with an explanation

28
00:01:19,159 --> 00:01:22,442
about what accessibility is and why it's important.

29
00:01:24,303 --> 00:01:28,107
And as I said, when I talk about accessibility, I'm talking about relating to disability.

30
00:01:28,407 --> 00:01:29,988
So sorry?

31
00:01:32,090 --> 00:01:32,671
Someone say something?

32
00:01:33,832 --> 00:01:34,152
I assume not.

33
00:01:35,145 --> 00:01:42,268
Cool, okay, right. So I'm going to start with an explanation about what disability is, and for that I have this gentleman here to help me.

34
00:01:44,648 --> 00:01:50,470
Now this image was taken as part of an investigation that he was doing for a newspaper back in the UK.

35
00:01:51,991 --> 00:01:59,773
And I'm sure when looking at this picture, most of the people in this room would be able to have some kind of a guess at what this guy's disability is.

36
00:02:00,314 --> 00:02:01,654
What it is that's making him disabled.

37
00:02:04,862 --> 00:02:08,205
So you might be thinking that perhaps he has cerebral palsy.

38
00:02:09,786 --> 00:02:11,047
In which case, you're kind of halfway there.

39
00:02:11,087 --> 00:02:14,489
He does have cerebral palsy, but cerebral palsy is not

40
00:02:14,609 --> 00:02:15,870
actually a disability.

41
00:02:16,831 --> 00:02:17,771
It's a medical condition.

42
00:02:18,392 --> 00:02:20,453
And that's a really important distinction to make.

43
00:02:23,015 --> 00:02:23,976
So what else could it be then?

44
00:02:24,356 --> 00:02:26,938
You might also be thinking about the fact that he is in a

45
00:02:27,198 --> 00:02:27,598
wheelchair.

46
00:02:30,040 --> 00:02:32,441
But again, a wheelchair is not a disability.

47
00:02:33,201 --> 00:02:34,762
It's like a pair of glasses.

48
00:02:35,362 --> 00:02:38,403
It's a piece of assistive technology that actually helps

49
00:02:38,463 --> 00:02:39,443
him go about his day.

50
00:02:41,724 --> 00:02:45,886
And he was going about his day fine until he went to meet his

51
00:02:45,966 --> 00:02:49,287
friends in this bar and encountered the steps.

52
00:02:50,917 --> 00:02:55,100
So in the context of meeting his friends in this bar, he is being disabled by the steps.

53
00:02:56,140 --> 00:03:01,123
And that's what disability actually is. It's when someone's medical condition encounters

54
00:03:01,163 --> 00:03:07,867
some kind of barrier, resulting in difficulty performing a day-to-day task. So it's a mismatch

55
00:03:07,907 --> 00:03:09,508
between a person and their environment.

56
00:03:11,454 --> 00:03:16,136
And the barriers that people face, whether it is steps in front of a bar,

57
00:03:16,956 --> 00:03:18,957
whether it is a shelf that's too high,

58
00:03:19,697 --> 00:03:21,778
whether it is red and green teams in a deathmatch,

59
00:03:23,398 --> 00:03:26,539
these barriers are often put there by another person.

60
00:03:27,800 --> 00:03:29,140
So we're designed to be like that.

61
00:03:31,221 --> 00:03:33,041
Which is kind of a heavy thing to get your head around,

62
00:03:33,061 --> 00:03:35,702
that as designers, as developers, as content producers,

63
00:03:36,183 --> 00:03:38,763
we are actually contributing to people's disability.

64
00:03:40,574 --> 00:03:44,477
But there is also the flip side to that, which is by being aware of the kind of barriers

65
00:03:44,518 --> 00:03:49,662
that people can encounter, we can figure out which of those barriers are unnecessary and

66
00:03:49,702 --> 00:03:54,346
avoid them and remove them and prevent disabling situations like these from occurring.

67
00:03:55,587 --> 00:03:57,869
And it's that process that's known as accessibility.

68
00:04:00,249 --> 00:04:03,052
Accessibility is important. It's important for many, many reasons.

69
00:04:03,352 --> 00:04:07,055
But one of those reasons is that people with disabilities are a market.

70
00:04:08,116 --> 00:04:09,638
And not an insignificant market either.

71
00:04:10,258 --> 00:04:13,842
The latest US government data is 22% of the adult population of the USA.

72
00:04:16,584 --> 00:04:19,965
Now, not everyone in that 22% is going to encounter barriers with games.

73
00:04:20,885 --> 00:04:24,946
That's more than balanced out by the other conditions that aren't included in that 22%.

74
00:04:25,406 --> 00:04:29,247
There's also color blindness, which affects 8% of males.

75
00:04:30,747 --> 00:04:34,388
Simulation sickness, estimates of that range anything from 10% upwards.

76
00:04:35,528 --> 00:04:40,470
Difficulty reading, now this is the one that surprises people because you don't hear about it because there's such a stigma.

77
00:04:41,050 --> 00:04:42,630
Difficulty reading affects 14% of adults.

78
00:04:46,261 --> 00:04:47,961
And this is just talking about permanent conditions.

79
00:04:48,001 --> 00:04:50,122
There's also temporary impairments,

80
00:04:50,942 --> 00:04:53,103
like having a broken arm, like RSI.

81
00:04:54,023 --> 00:04:55,743
There's also situational impairments,

82
00:04:56,364 --> 00:04:57,764
like having to play a game on mute

83
00:04:57,964 --> 00:05:00,545
because the baby's asleep, playing in direct sunlight.

84
00:05:00,565 --> 00:05:02,945
So there's all kinds of situations

85
00:05:02,965 --> 00:05:04,506
where these kind of barriers occur.

86
00:05:05,626 --> 00:05:06,746
Large, large numbers of people.

87
00:05:07,086 --> 00:05:08,106
And also these large numbers

88
00:05:08,547 --> 00:05:10,027
equate into large amounts of business,

89
00:05:10,407 --> 00:05:12,027
money to be made, money to be lost

90
00:05:12,328 --> 00:05:13,288
through these kind of decisions.

91
00:05:16,009 --> 00:05:19,660
And the other really, really important reason for considering accessibility is something

92
00:05:19,680 --> 00:05:20,824
that's a bit less mercenary.

93
00:05:21,125 --> 00:05:23,091
It's the human benefit of accessibility.

94
00:05:25,199 --> 00:05:31,923
Because what games actually represent is access to recreation, to culture, to socializing,

95
00:05:33,164 --> 00:05:35,866
which are things that so many of us just take for granted.

96
00:05:36,987 --> 00:05:42,910
But if for any reason in your day-to-day life your means of accessing those things is restricted,

97
00:05:44,511 --> 00:05:49,554
games can then provide them and become a really important contributor to someone's quality

98
00:05:49,574 --> 00:05:49,855
of life.

99
00:05:53,217 --> 00:05:56,419
Or, to explain all of that in a much more concise way than I have,

100
00:05:56,439 --> 00:05:59,101
it's one of my favorite quotes.

101
00:06:04,364 --> 00:06:08,387
So because accessibility is so important, it's been really, really nice to see

102
00:06:09,007 --> 00:06:11,949
the field advancing, more and more progress being made every year,

103
00:06:13,550 --> 00:06:15,392
increasing exponentially every year.

104
00:06:15,412 --> 00:06:17,233
You see more and more and more, faster and faster,

105
00:06:17,273 --> 00:06:18,474
and the last year is no exception.

106
00:06:19,694 --> 00:06:20,875
But going back a little bit further,

107
00:06:22,814 --> 00:06:29,479
The big advance of 2015 was the introduction of accessibility functionality on consoles,

108
00:06:31,020 --> 00:06:35,784
on both the PlayStation 4 and the Xbox One. And this includes stuff like text-to-speech

109
00:06:36,464 --> 00:06:41,068
so that people who are blind can navigate the system interface, high contrast mode,

110
00:06:41,789 --> 00:06:45,612
zoom, remapping the controls at system level. All this stuff was added in.

111
00:06:46,912 --> 00:06:48,293
And that's continued on into 2016.

112
00:06:48,353 --> 00:06:51,034
So neither company has been resting on their laurels.

113
00:06:51,054 --> 00:06:55,597
They've continued to add in more functionality, like control over text speed, improved text

114
00:06:55,617 --> 00:06:56,197
size options.

115
00:06:57,117 --> 00:06:58,278
This is another nice example.

116
00:06:58,318 --> 00:07:01,359
This is the addition of clubs onto Xbox One.

117
00:07:02,040 --> 00:07:06,062
And you can see here it's being used by deaf gamers to find other people to play with who

118
00:07:06,142 --> 00:07:08,563
aren't going to kick them out of a game because they can't use a microphone.

119
00:07:12,935 --> 00:07:14,476
And it hasn't just been the consoles either.

120
00:07:14,516 --> 00:07:16,257
It's now starting to spread further.

121
00:07:16,838 --> 00:07:20,180
So this is Steam Big Picture mode, which now allows, again,

122
00:07:20,500 --> 00:07:21,500
full button remapping.

123
00:07:25,322 --> 00:07:28,444
And also Steam have open sourced their Lighthouse

124
00:07:28,484 --> 00:07:32,206
technology, which opens the door to custom

125
00:07:32,547 --> 00:07:33,467
input devices for VR.

126
00:07:35,238 --> 00:07:38,499
But this button remapping stuff, remapping at platform

127
00:07:38,539 --> 00:07:42,200
level, both in Steam and on the consoles, is really good

128
00:07:42,260 --> 00:07:45,502
as a safety net, but it's not as good as remapping in a game.

129
00:07:46,402 --> 00:07:48,843
If you have actual in-game remapping, that opens up

130
00:07:48,883 --> 00:07:51,944
things like being able to have separate maps for walking and

131
00:07:51,984 --> 00:07:54,785
for driving, or like in Overwatch, being able to have

132
00:07:54,845 --> 00:07:56,385
separate mappings for each character class.

133
00:07:56,966 --> 00:07:59,607
It also allows you to do things like have your in-game

134
00:07:59,627 --> 00:08:02,528
tutorials and prompts update to reflect what the current

135
00:08:02,568 --> 00:08:02,888
mapping is.

136
00:08:04,985 --> 00:08:06,729
But there is a barrier to that, which is the cost of

137
00:08:06,749 --> 00:08:11,340
implementing it, which is in the process

138
00:08:11,360 --> 00:08:12,101
of being broken down.

139
00:08:15,312 --> 00:08:18,533
So I think it was around April 2016, Unity announced that

140
00:08:18,574 --> 00:08:21,735
they were working on a new input model, which it hasn't

141
00:08:22,156 --> 00:08:24,297
hit general public release yet, but they're developing it

142
00:08:24,357 --> 00:08:25,558
collaboratively with developers.

143
00:08:25,698 --> 00:08:27,519
So you can actually already go on the site and download it

144
00:08:27,559 --> 00:08:28,439
and have a play around with it.

145
00:08:29,360 --> 00:08:34,062
And the basic principle is it just abstracts out inputs and

146
00:08:34,162 --> 00:08:35,823
actions by default.

147
00:08:37,847 --> 00:08:40,531
So an input being, for example, the A button, an action

148
00:08:40,571 --> 00:08:41,072
being jump.

149
00:08:41,813 --> 00:08:42,394
They're separate.

150
00:08:42,634 --> 00:08:44,657
And to create a control scheme, a developer just

151
00:08:44,737 --> 00:08:47,020
creates relationships, creates links between those things,

152
00:08:47,581 --> 00:08:49,824
which means the functionality is already there for players

153
00:08:49,884 --> 00:08:50,565
to do the same thing.

154
00:08:52,027 --> 00:08:57,652
And basically because Unity wants to support input devices that haven't even been invented yet,

155
00:08:58,252 --> 00:09:01,334
you know, the pace at which things are being invented for VR and stuff like that,

156
00:09:02,735 --> 00:09:05,677
they wanted to make sure that all different types of input work together,

157
00:09:06,498 --> 00:09:08,640
which means that it can do things like, for example,

158
00:09:08,900 --> 00:09:12,322
remap a controller-based control scheme to a keyboard or a mouse.

159
00:09:12,883 --> 00:09:14,564
You can remap analog to digital,

160
00:09:14,944 --> 00:09:18,587
so you can move a command between, like, the B button and pushing forward on an analog stick.

161
00:09:19,027 --> 00:09:21,089
So this is all quite difficult stuff for developers to do,

162
00:09:21,109 --> 00:09:23,331
and it's all just going to be handled for you at engine level.

163
00:09:28,916 --> 00:09:31,318
And there's also been some nice platform-level advances

164
00:09:31,458 --> 00:09:33,019
outside the dedicated gaming space.

165
00:09:35,121 --> 00:09:37,764
So what you're looking at here is an iPad on the right.

166
00:09:38,824 --> 00:09:41,947
And the iPad is being operated solely by the yellow button.

167
00:09:44,152 --> 00:09:46,474
And that yellow button is something that's known as an

168
00:09:46,634 --> 00:09:47,614
accessibility switch.

169
00:09:48,455 --> 00:09:51,397
And it's called a switch because it's a simple on-off

170
00:09:51,957 --> 00:09:52,458
interaction.

171
00:09:53,818 --> 00:09:56,300
And those kind of input devices, they can take lots of

172
00:09:56,320 --> 00:09:56,900
different forms.

173
00:09:57,000 --> 00:09:57,881
It could be a button like that.

174
00:09:58,541 --> 00:10:00,082
A common setup is a button mounted on a

175
00:10:00,122 --> 00:10:00,923
wheelchair headrest.

176
00:10:01,723 --> 00:10:03,184
It could be a tube you blow into.

177
00:10:05,046 --> 00:10:06,486
It could be an infrared link detector.

178
00:10:06,687 --> 00:10:08,868
It's the same kind of kit that Stephen Hawking uses to

179
00:10:08,908 --> 00:10:09,568
operate technology.

180
00:10:12,119 --> 00:10:16,383
And iOS is compatible with this, like at an operating system level.

181
00:10:16,403 --> 00:10:19,105
You can operate the whole of an iPhone, of an iPad,

182
00:10:19,165 --> 00:10:20,986
just using a single input.

183
00:10:22,347 --> 00:10:23,488
And it has a couple of different modes.

184
00:10:23,668 --> 00:10:27,311
One of them is basically it works like shooting in a basketball game.

185
00:10:27,952 --> 00:10:30,754
So you have a line that moves across the screen.

186
00:10:33,461 --> 00:10:34,141
Sorry, wrong one.

187
00:10:35,142 --> 00:10:36,503
So you have a line that moves left and right

188
00:10:36,523 --> 00:10:37,124
across the screen.

189
00:10:38,004 --> 00:10:40,706
When it reaches the coordinate you want, you make your input,

190
00:10:41,006 --> 00:10:41,407
it stops.

191
00:10:42,367 --> 00:10:43,888
Then the line moves up and down.

192
00:10:43,908 --> 00:10:45,490
You choose the coordinate you want.

193
00:10:46,550 --> 00:10:48,452
Once you've chosen the coordinate on the screen, it

194
00:10:48,512 --> 00:10:50,973
pops up a little menu and asks you what you would like to do

195
00:10:51,294 --> 00:10:53,375
at that point, whether you want to tap, whether you want to

196
00:10:53,415 --> 00:10:54,416
swipe, whether you want to zoom.

197
00:10:56,853 --> 00:10:59,957
Which already makes a lot of games accessible.

198
00:11:00,838 --> 00:11:04,542
So you can imagine a basic interface type game like Football Manager, something like that.

199
00:11:04,763 --> 00:11:06,185
You can operate using this technology.

200
00:11:06,625 --> 00:11:10,069
So like this guy's doing, Christopher, he's using a single button on his wheelchair headrest.

201
00:11:12,352 --> 00:11:15,416
Not so good if you're playing something like Flappy Birds, for example.

202
00:11:16,357 --> 00:11:18,880
So Flappy Birds, in theory, is just a single input.

203
00:11:19,060 --> 00:11:20,462
It should work with this kind of technology.

204
00:11:21,283 --> 00:11:23,725
But using the scanning from side to side system, you can

205
00:11:23,745 --> 00:11:27,750
imagine you move across, move down, hit the Start button,

206
00:11:28,330 --> 00:11:30,713
start moving across, and that's happened.

207
00:11:34,518 --> 00:11:35,479
That has now changed.

208
00:11:36,619 --> 00:11:38,281
This has been really, really exciting to see.

209
00:11:38,301 --> 00:11:41,623
In the past year, Apple, in response to requests, has

210
00:11:41,683 --> 00:11:44,625
actually done two specific updates to this functionality

211
00:11:45,185 --> 00:11:46,026
specific to games.

212
00:11:47,407 --> 00:11:51,890
So the first one being in iOS 9, they added the ability to

213
00:11:52,030 --> 00:11:54,552
choose a point on the screen and then tap repeatedly at

214
00:11:54,592 --> 00:11:57,234
that point, which means that games like Canabalt, games

215
00:11:57,254 --> 00:11:59,976
like Flappy Birds, now just work with that kind of

216
00:11:59,996 --> 00:12:00,396
technology.

217
00:12:01,974 --> 00:12:07,918
iOS 10, they upgraded it again, allowing you to hold down at a point repeatedly, which

218
00:12:07,938 --> 00:12:12,942
means games like Alto's Adventure, games like Badlands, just work with this kind of technology,

219
00:12:13,923 --> 00:12:18,907
which is a really, really amazing example of the power of operating systems to facilitate

220
00:12:18,927 --> 00:12:19,467
this kind of stuff.

221
00:12:19,487 --> 00:12:25,152
Because it just means thousands of games overnight now just work with this kind of technology

222
00:12:25,592 --> 00:12:27,213
without any effort from developers at all.

223
00:12:35,323 --> 00:12:37,323
There's also been advances in games themselves.

224
00:12:40,744 --> 00:12:42,584
Now, in the games media this year, there's been two things

225
00:12:42,644 --> 00:12:43,985
above all else that have really, really

226
00:12:44,045 --> 00:12:45,005
dominated the media.

227
00:12:45,505 --> 00:12:47,085
The first one being Pokemon Go.

228
00:12:48,666 --> 00:12:51,106
And Pokemon Go is actually accessible with this kind of

229
00:12:51,126 --> 00:12:52,446
switch technology that I'm talking about.

230
00:12:52,947 --> 00:12:54,827
So what you can see on the screen here is after you've

231
00:12:54,847 --> 00:12:57,147
chosen a coordinate, it gives you the little menu, the

232
00:12:57,187 --> 00:12:58,428
palette of actions you can choose.

233
00:12:58,928 --> 00:13:01,508
So you can see here it's choosing a flick to flick the

234
00:13:01,528 --> 00:13:01,848
Pokeball.

235
00:13:04,523 --> 00:13:08,236
But despite this, Pokemon in general is not a very accessible game.

236
00:13:10,156 --> 00:13:12,797
Now, some of that is due to the physicality of the game,

237
00:13:13,217 --> 00:13:15,578
the fact that you have to be climbing up hills and stuff

238
00:13:15,598 --> 00:13:15,898
to play it.

239
00:13:16,799 --> 00:13:19,600
But a lot of it is actually just due to simple interface

240
00:13:19,640 --> 00:13:23,221
decisions, so things like these complex gestures, that

241
00:13:23,301 --> 00:13:26,522
has small, low-contrast text, which is obviously not great

242
00:13:26,562 --> 00:13:28,223
for a game that you're supposed to play outdoors in

243
00:13:28,243 --> 00:13:28,683
the sunlight.

244
00:13:29,724 --> 00:13:32,305
Also, the map screen, the elements in the map screen

245
00:13:32,405 --> 00:13:34,726
that are distinguished by color alone, not so great if

246
00:13:34,746 --> 00:13:35,186
you're colorblind.

